# Deobfuscated Code & Explanation

## Deobfuscated Version

```javascript
var TWO_PI = Math.PI * 2;

// Configuration constants
var config = {
    repulsionK: 4000,       // Repulsion force constant
    springK: 0.004,         // Default spring stiffness
    damping: 0.92,          // Velocity damping factor
    gravity: 0.0003,        // Gravity toward center
    particleMax: 40,        // Max number of particles
    particleFade: 0.04,     // Particle fade rate
    cameraEase: 0.06        // Camera easing factor
};

// Define nodes in the graph
var nodes = [
    { id: 'alpha',    label: 'Hub',       r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'beta',     label: 'Beta',      r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'gamma',    label: 'Gamma',     r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'gamma',    label: 'Delta',     r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'delta',    label: 'Delta',     r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
    { id: 'epsilon',  label: 'Epsilon',   r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// Define edges (springs) connecting nodes
var edges = [
    { a: 'alpha', b: 'beta',    rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
    { a: 'alpha', b: 'gamma',   rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
    { a: 'alpha', b: 'gamma',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
    { a: 'alpha', b: 'delta',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
    { a: 'alpha', b: 'epsilon', rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
    { a: 'beta',  b: 'beta',    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
    { a: 'gamma', b: 'delta',   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
    { a: 'alpha', b: 'epsilon', rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// Camera state (current and target)
var camera       = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
var cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

var particles = [];
var frameCount = 0;

// Find a node by its ID
function findNode(id) {
    for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
        if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
    }
    return null;
}

// Physics simulation step
function simulate() {
    // 1. Apply repulsion between all node pairs (Coulomb-like force)
    for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
        for (var j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
            var dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
            var dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
            var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
            var force = config.repulsionK / (dist * dist);
            var fx = (dx / dist) * force;
            var fy = (dy / dist) * force;
            nodes[i].vx += fx;
            nodes[i].vy += fy;
            nodes[j].vx -= fx;
            nodes[j].vy -= fy;
        }
    }

    // 2. Apply spring forces along edges (Hooke's law)
    for (var e = 0; e < edges.length; e++) {
        var nodeA = findNode(edges[e].a);
        var nodeB = findNode(edges[e].b);
        if (!nodeA || !nodeB) continue;
        var dx = nodeB.x - nodeA.x;
        var dy = nodeB.y - nodeA.y;
        var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
        var displacement = dist - edges[e].rest;
        var force = (edges[e].k || config.springK) * displacement;
        nodeA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
        nodeA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
        nodeB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
        nodeB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
    }

    // 3. Apply damping, centering gravity, and update positions
    for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
        nodes[i].vx += (400 - nodes[i].x) * config.gravity;  // pull toward center x=400
        nodes[i].vy += (300 - nodes[i].y) * config.gravity;  // pull toward center y=300
        nodes[i].vx *= config.damping;
        nodes[i].vy *= config.damping;
        nodes[i].x += nodes[i].vx;
        nodes[i].y += nodes[i].vy;
    }
}

// Spawn a particle from a random node
function spawnParticle() {
    if (particles.length >= config.particleMax) return;
    var node = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
    var angle = Math.random() * TWO_PI;
    var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * 0.7;
    particles.push({
        x: node.x,
        y: node.y,
        vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
        vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
        age: 0,
        maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
        size: 0.8 + Math.random() * 1.2
    });
}

// Update all particles
function updateParticles() {
    for (var i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        var p = particles[i];
        p.vx *= 0.995;   // slight drag
        p.vy *= 0.995;
        p.x += p.vx;
        p.y += p.vy;
        p.age++;
        if (p.age > p.maxAge) particles.splice(i, 1);  // remove dead particles
    }
}

// Ease camera toward target
function updateCamera() {
    camera.x += (cameraTarget.x - camera.x) * config.cameraEase;
    camera.y += (cameraTarget.y - camera.y) * config.cameraEase;
    camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.cameraEase;
}

// Main update loop
function tick() {
    simulate();
    updateCamera();
    if (frameCount % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();
    updateParticles();
    frameCount++;
}

setInterval(tick, 16);  // ~60 FPS
```

## What It Does

This is a **force-directed graph simulation** — a common technique for visualizing network/graph data. Here's the breakdown:

### 🔵 Nodes
Six nodes (named `alpha` through `epsilon`, with `alpha` as the central "Hub") are placed on a 2D canvas. Each has a position, velocity, and radius.

### 🔗 Edges (Springs)
Eight spring connections link the nodes together with **Hooke's law** — each spring has a rest length and stiffness constant. Springs pull connected nodes toward their rest distance.

### ⚡ Physics Engine (runs every ~16ms)
1. **Repulsion** — All node pairs repel each other (like electric charges) to prevent overlap
2. **Spring attraction** — Connected nodes are pulled toward their ideal distance
3. **Centering gravity** — A weak force pulls everything toward the center point (400, 300)
4. **Damping** — Velocities are multiplied by 0.92 each frame to prevent infinite oscillation

### ✨ Particles
Decorative particles spawn from random nodes every 3 frames, drift outward with slight drag, and are removed when they exceed their lifespan. This creates an ambient "energy" visual effect.

### 🎥 Camera
A camera system smoothly eases toward a target position/zoom using linear interpolation.

**In summary:** This is the physics/logic backend for an animated, interactive network graph visualization with decorative floating particles and a smooth camera — likely rendered elsewhere on an HTML canvas.
